\description{
Calculates \strong{intensity-Based Absolute Quantification (iBAQ)} values from
DIA-NN search results (\code{report.parquet}) and a reference proteome FASTA
file.

The iBAQ method normalises the summed precursor intensities of a protein by
the number of theoretically observable tryptic peptides, making protein
abundances comparable regardless of protein size:

\deqn{iBAQ = \frac{\sum \text{precursor intensities}}{\text{# theoretical peptides}}}
}
\details{
Compute iBAQ values from a DIA-NN report and a reference proteome FASTA
\subsection{Workflow}{
\enumerate{
\item \strong{Load} the DIA-NN \code{report.parquet} using \code{\link[arrow:read_parquet]{arrow::read_parquet()}}.
\item \strong{Filter} low-quality precursors via \code{\link[=filter_diann_report]{filter_diann_report()}}.
\item \strong{Aggregate} precursor intensities to the protein × sample level.
Each unique stripped peptide sequence is counted once per sample (even
if observed with multiple charge states or modifications), then summed
per protein per sample.
\item \strong{Parse} the FASTA and count theoretically observable tryptic peptides
per protein using \code{\link[=build_theoretical_peptide_counts]{build_theoretical_peptide_counts()}}.
\item \strong{Divide} the summed intensity by the theoretical peptide count.
\item \strong{Optionally} log2-transform: \code{log2(iBAQ + 1)} (adds a pseudo-count of
1 to avoid \code{log2(0)}).
\item \strong{Return} a wide- or long-format tibble.
}
}

\subsection{References}{
\itemize{
\item Schwanhäusser B et al. (2011). Global quantification of mammalian gene
expression control. \emph{Nature} \strong{473}:337–342.
\doi{10.1038/nature10098}
\item 41ison/iBAQ-for-DIANN (GitHub reference implementation)
\item bigbio/ibaqpy (Python reference implementation)
}
}
